(31, 'UG', 1, 'maharashtra-ayush', 'Maharashtra Ayush Admission Process', './assets/images/MHTCET.jpeg', 'Maharashtra Ayush Admission Process', 'Introduction\r\nThe Ministry of Ayush was formed on the 9th of November 2014 with a vision of reviving the profound knowledge of our ancient systems of medicine and ensuring the optimal development and propagation of the Ayush systems of healthcare. Earlier, the Department of Indian System of Medicine and Homoeopathy (ISM&H) formed in 1995, was responsible for the development of these systems. It was then renamed as the Department of Ayurveda, Yoga, and Naturopathy, Unani, Siddha and Homoeopathy (Ayush) in November 2003 with focused attention towards education and research in Ayurveda, Yoga and Naturopathy, Unani, Siddha, and Homoeopathy.\r\n\r\n\r\nGovernment of India, Ministry of AYUSH, New Delhi, has authorised to the State Counselling Authority to conduct the counselling for admission in All India Quota (15%) Seats of Private Unaided/Minority Institutions for the Academic Year 2024-25. Admission to Maharashtra AYUSH Counselling 2024 is determined by various factors, including the choices made by students, their NEET 2023 state rank, and the Maharashtra AYUSH Counselling 2023 cutoff scores.', 'Eligibility\r\nHSC Passing Marks for eligibility\r\nCategory	Information\r\nGeneral Category	Must have obtained not less than 50% marks in Physics, Chemistry and Biology taken together at the HSC\r\nScheduled Castes, Scheduled Tribes and Other Backward Classes (as per centre list)	Must have obtained not less than 40% (i.e. 120 out of 300) marks in Physics, Chemistry and Biology taken together at the HSC (or equivalent) Examination.\r\nGeneral Category (PWD)	45% in Physics, Chemistry and Biology\r\nScheduled Castes, Scheduled Tribes and Other Backward Classes (PWD)	40% in Physics, Chemistry and Biology\r\n\r\nNEET Passing Marks for eligibility\r\nGeneral Category	Minimum 50 Percentile in NEET UG.\r\nScheduled Caste, Scheduled Tribes and Other Backward	Minimum 40 Percentile in NEET UG.\r\nGeneral Category (PWD)	Minimum 45 Percentile in NEET UG.\r\nScheduled Castes, Scheduled Tribes and Other Backward Classes (PWD)	Minimum 40th Percentile in NEET UG.', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	\r\nReservation Percentage\r\nScheduled Caste (SC)	15%\r\nSchedule Tribe (ST)	7.5%\r\nOther Backward Classes (NCL)	27%\r\nGeneral	10%\r\nPerson with Disability (PwD)	5%', '\r\nFee Structure           Amount\r\n\r\nRegistration Fees      Rs.2000/\r\nSecurity Deposit       Rs. 50,000/-\r\n\r\nThe Security Deposit will be forfeited if a candidate does not join the allotted Seat of Round-2 or surrender/withdraw the seat allotted in Round-2 based on Candidate\'s request. Further, the security deposit will also be forfeited if the allotted seat of Round-2 is cancelled due to any unforeseen reason from the candidate’s end.', 'Process Flow\r\n\r\nOnline Registration for NEET UG - (Ayurveda/ Homoeopathy/Unani) 2023 (All India Quota) only in Private College on website at www.mahacet.org\r\nPayment of Registration fees through Online Payment Gateway\r\n\r\nUploading of all required Coloured Scan Original Documents in pdf after Successful Payment\r\n\r\nCap \r\nRound 1\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nROnline Registration for NEET UG - (Ayurveda/ Homoeopathy/Unani) 2023 (All India Quota) only in Private College on website at www.mahacet.org Payment of Registration fees through Online Payment Gateway\r\n\r\nUploading of all required Coloured Scan Original Documents in pdf after Successful Payment\r\n\r\nPublication of Provisional State Merit List\r\n\r\nPublication of Seat Matrix for NEET UG 2023 (Ayurveda/ Homoeopathy/Unani) 2023 - AIQ\r\n\r\nOnline Filling of Preference Form for CAP Round-1\r\n\r\nPhysical Joining and Filling of Status Retention Form with All Original Documents & Requisite Fees by DD/Cheque\r\n\r\nLast date of resignation of CAP Round -1 Seats without forfeiture of fees\r\n\r\n\r\nCap \r\nRound 2\r\n\r\nPublication of Seat Matrix for NEET UG (Ayurveda/ Homoeopathy/Unani) 2023 - AIQ\r\n\r\nOnline Registration for NEET UG - (Ayurveda/ Homoeopathy/Unani) 2023 (All India Quota) only in Pvt College on website at www.mahacet.org CAP-2\r\n\r\nPayment of Registration Fees (Rs.2000/-) (NOT REFUNDABLE) (Candidates Registered During CAP-1 need not register again)\r\n\r\nPublication of combined Registered Candidates List (AIQ)\r\n\r\nOnline Filling of Preference Form for CAP Round-2\r\n\r\nDeclaration of CAP Round - 2 Selection List\r\n\r\nPhysical Joining and Filling of Status Retention Form with All Original Documents & Requisite Fees by DD/Cheque\r\n\r\nLast date of resignation of CAP- 2 seats with forfeiture of registration fees', 'What is the MAHARASHTRA AYUSH Admission Process?\r\nMaharashtra AYUSH admission is done through online CAP (Centralised Admission Process) counselling** conducted by the Maharashtra State Common Entrance Test Cell for AYUSH courses like BAMS (Ayurveda), BHMS (Homeopathy), and BUMS (Unani)** based on the NEET‑UG 2025 score and merit list. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nWho is eligible for Maharashtra AYUSH admission?\r\nCandidates must have qualified NEET‑UG 2025, meet eligibility criteria such as minimum age and passing Class 12 with Physics, Chemistry & Biology, and must complete online registration on the official CET Cell portal. ([Careers360][2])\r\n\r\n How do I register for AYUSH counselling in Maharashtra?\r\n You must register online on the Maharashtra CET Cell counselling website during the specified registration window, upload required documents, pay the registration & security deposit fees, and complete the choice filling process. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nWhat are the main steps in the AYUSH counselling process?**\r\n The admission process includes:\r\n\r\n1.Online registration & fee payment\r\n2.Upload documents & verification\r\n3.Choice filling and locking (preference of colleges & courses)\r\n4.Seat allotment based on merit and preferences\r\n5.Reporting to the allotted institute with original documents\r\n6.Further CAP rounds or Stray Vacancy Rounds as applicable. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nHow many rounds are there in the Maharashtra AYUSH counselling?\r\nThe counselling usually has multiple CAP rounds (Round 1, Round 2, Round 3) and Online Stray Vacancy Rounds for leftover seats if available. ([Careers360][2])\r\n\r\nCan I participate in a fresh round if I get no seat or want better colleges?\r\n Yes — if you are not allotted a seat or want a better option, you can fill choices in the next CAP round (fresh choice filling as per schedule). ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nWhat happens during choice filling and locking?**\r\nCandidates must enter their preferred colleges and course codes online within the given dates and the choices before the deadline. Once locked, preferences can’t be changed for that round. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\n Is there a Stray Vacancy Round in the MAHARASHTRA AYUSH admission process?\r\n Yes — if seats remain vacant after the main CAP rounds, Online Stray Vacancy Rounds are conducted to fill remaining seats based on merit and preferences. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nDo I need to report to the college after seat allotment?**\r\nYes — after seat allotment, you must report to the allotted college within the specified time with all original documents for verification and admission confirmation. ([Ayush Counselling 2025][1])\r\n\r\nAre candidates from other states eligible for Maharashtra AYUSH counselling?\r\nInstitutional quota seats may be available for candidates **from outside Maharashtra, but eligibility and quota rules differ. ([Careers360][2])\r\n', NULL, 5, 1, '2026-01-07 10:39:14', '2026-01-09 06:52:09'),
(32, 'UG', 1, 'veterinary-council-india', 'Veterinary Council of India Process', './assets/images/VCIP.jpeg', 'Veterinary Council of India Process', 'Introduction\r\nThe Veterinary Council of India (VCI) is a statutory body Established by an Act of Parliament viz Indian Veterinary Council (IVC) Act, 1984 under the Department of Animal Husbandry & Dairying, Government of India for regulation of veterinary practice, veterinary education and preparation and maintenance of Indian Veterinary Practitioner\'s Register.\r\n\r\n15% of the total seats allowed for admission in recognized veterinary colleges (included in First Schedule to the IVC Act, 1984) shall be filled by Veterinary Council of India on the NEET (UG) 2023 Examination conducted by National Testing Agency (NTA). In pursuance of letter issued by the Department of Animal Husbandry Dairying and Ministry of Fisheries, Animal Husbandry and Dairying, Government of India, Veterinary Council of India will use merit list of National Eligibility cum Entrance Test (UG)-2023 (NEET (UG)-2023) conducted by National Testing Agency (NTA) for filling up 15% seats in the recognized Veterinary Colleges under All India Quota during the Academic Session 2024-25. Other criteria of selection and admission to B.V.Sc. &. A.H. Degree course shall be as per Veterinary Council of India - MSVE, Degree Course (B.V.Sc. & A.H.) Regulations, 2016.', 'Eligibility\r\nNationality\r\n\r\nCandidate should be Indian National. The Overseas Citizen of India (OCI) / Person with Indian Origin (PIO) also will be eligible for online registration for counselling for admission to B.V.Sc. &A.H. course under the 15% quota\r\n\r\nAge\r\n\r\nThe candidate must have attained minimum age of 17 years as on 31st December, 2023.\r\n\r\n\r\nEssential Qualification\r\n\r\nQualification	Unreserved Category	Reserved Category\r\nXII th Std. passed in 10+2 pattern or an equivalent Examination ( Physics , Chemistry, Biology or Biotechnology and English )	Minimum 50%	Minimum 47.50%', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	Quota\r\nSC candidates	15%\r\nST candidates	7.5%\r\nEWS candidates	10%\r\nOBC candidates (Non Creamy Layer)	27%\r\n*5% seats in each category are reserved for Physically Handicapped candidates.', 'Fee Structure\r\n\r\nRegistration Fee for Round 1, Round 2, & MOPUP Round\r\nCategory	Amount\r\nGeneral candidates	Rs. 1000/-\r\nEWS /OBC candidates	Rs 900/-\r\nSC/ST/PWD(PH)/Transgender candidates	Rs 500/-\r\n\r\nMOP-UP Round Fees (Seacurity Deposite Refundable Subject to Certain Condition)\r\nCategory	Amount\r\nGeneral/ OBC/EWS/PIO	Rs. 10000/-\r\nSC/ST/PH/ Transgender	Rs 5000/-\r\n\r\nStray Round Participation Fees\r\nCategory	Amount\r\nGeneral/ OBC/EWS/PIO	Rs. 50000/-\r\nSC/ST/PH/ Transgender	Rs 25000/-', 'Process Flow\r\nRound 1\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRegistration and payment of Fees\r\n\r\nChoices filling and locking\r\n\r\nDownload the Provisional Allotment Letter after the result, if allotted\r\n\r\nReporting at the College (Candidates those who have reported at the College will have option for re-choice filling in Round -2)\r\n\r\nNote :-The candidate who have been allotted seat in Round -1 but not reported for admission to the allotted college shall not be allowed to participate in further round of counselling\r\n\r\n\r\nRound 2\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRegistration and payment of Fees by fresh candidates (Only for the fresh candidates who have neither registered nor paid registration fees in Round -1)\r\n\r\nThe candidates registered in Round -1 with payment of fees need not have to register separately for Round - 2\r\n\r\nChoices filling and locking\r\n\r\nDownload the Provisional Allotment Letter after the result, if allotted. Reporting at the College\r\n\r\n\r\nMOP-UP Round\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRegistration for Mop-up Round and payment of Registration fee by fresh candidates\r\n\r\nNote :- 1. Candidates registered in Round - 1 or Round - 2 but not allotted seat need not to re - register for participating in the Mop-up Round. 2. Candidates who are allotted seat in Round -1 or Round -2 are not eligible to participate in the Mop-up Round.\r\n\r\nPayment of Mop-up Round Fee (Security Deposit)\r\n\r\nChoices filling and locking\r\n\r\nDownload the Provisional Allotment Letter after the result, if allotted\r\n\r\nReporting at the College\r\n\r\n\r\nStray Round\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNotification of available Vacant seats\r\n\r\nThere shall not be fresh registration for Stray Round. The candidates already registered in Mop Round and not allotted any seats in the aforesaid Round are eligible for Stray Round. However, candidate has to make Payment for Stray Round Participation Fee (Security deposit) as per schedule time\r\n\r\nChoices filling and locking\r\n\r\nDownload the Provisional Allotment Letter after the result, if allotted\r\n\r\nReporting at the College', '\r\nWhat does VCI do?\r\n The main functions of VCI include setting minimum standards for veterinary education, recognising or withdrawing recognition of veterinary qualifications, maintaining a register of qualified veterinary practitioners, and promoting ethical conduct and professional standards in veterinary practice.\r\n\r\nHow are veterinary admissions organised under VCI?\r\nVeterinary admissions under VCI, especially for the 15% All India Quota (AIQ) of BVSc & AH seats, are conducted online through the VCI counselling portal. Candidates must qualify NEET-UG and then complete registration, choice filling, and seat allotment online for AIQ seats.\r\n\r\nWhat is the VCI counselling process?\r\nThe VCI counselling process includes online registration and fee payment on the VCI admissions portal, choice filling and locking of preferred veterinary colleges and programs, seat allotment based on NEET rank, category, and preferences, downloading the allotment letter, and reporting to the allotted institute with the required documents. Further rounds, such as Round 2 and Stray Vacancy rounds, are conducted if seats remain vacant.\r\n\r\nWhat documents are needed for VCI counselling?\r\n Candidates are required to submit documents such as NEET Admit Card and Scorecard, 10th/12th mark sheets and certificates, identity proof, category/domicile certificates (if applicable), passport-size photos, and any other certificates specified in the information brochure.\r\n\r\nCan I change my choices during counselling?\r\n During counselling, candidates can add, delete, reorder, or modify their choices before locking them within the prescribed schedule. If candidates do not lock their choices by the deadline, the system may automatically lock the last saved choices. Registered candidates who do not save any choices will not be considered for seat allotment.\r\n\r\nDo I need to report to the college after seat allotment?\r\n After seat allotment, candidates must report to their allotted veterinary college within the specified reporting window with the required documents for verification and admission confirmation.\r\n\r\nWhat happens if seats remain vacant after counselling rounds?\r\n If seats remain vacant after counselling rounds, VCI conducts subsequent rounds such as Round 2 and Stray Vacancy rounds to fill the remaining AIQ seats.\r\n\r\nDoes VCI handle state quota seats?** VCI only handles the 15% AIQ seats; the remaining 85% state quota seats are managed by the respective State Veterinary Universities or state counselling authorities.\r\n', NULL, 6, 1, '2026-01-07 10:39:14', '2026-01-09 06:57:05'),
(33, 'UG', 1, 'maharashtra-animal-fishery', 'Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University', './assets/images/MAFSU.jpeg', 'Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University', 'Introduction\r\nMaharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University, Nagpur has been constituted under of Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University Act, 1998 (Maharashtra Act XVII).\r\n\r\n•\r\nHon\'ble Governor of Maharashtra State and Chancellor of Maharashtra Animal & Fishery Sciences University, Nagpur\r\n•\r\nHon\'ble Minister of Animal Husbandry, Dairy Development and Fisheries, Maharashtra State and Pro-Chancellor of Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University, Nagpur\r\n•\r\nHon\'ble Vice-Chancellor, Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University, Nagpur\r\n\r\nIn exercise of the powers conferred upon University vide provision in section 5 (Chapter II) of the MAFSU Act, 1998, admission to the degree programme in the faculty of Veterinary Science shall be held in accordance with the following regulations.', 'Eligibility\r\nCriteria\r\n\r\nCriteria	Unreserved Category	Reserved Category\r\nXIIth Std. passed in 10+2 pattern or an equivalent Examination ( Physics , Chemistry, Biology or Biotechnology and English)	Minimum 50%	Minimum 47.50%\r\nAge Criteria	Minimum 17 years and should be below 25 years	Minimum 17 years and should be below 25 years (Relaxation of maximum age by 5 year)\r\n\r\nQuota\r\n\r\nUniversity Quota seats	70% seats of University quota at each constituent college shall be filled in as regional quota (R-quota) 30% of the seats of total intake capacity shall be filled as state quota (S-quota)\r\nVCI Quota seats	15% of total intake capacity of each Veterinary College shall be filled in by Veterinary Council of India (VCI), New Delhi through its independent admission procedure.\r\nJ&K and Ladakh UT Quota seats	One seat over and above the intake capacity at each Veterinary College shall be filled from the wards of citizens displaced due to terrorist activities from Jammu & Kashmir Union Territories and Ladakh Union Territories and also from the wards of officers belonging to Indian Administrative Services, Indian Police Services and other officers and staff belonging to military and paramilitary forces transferred to Jammu & Kashmir and Ladakh Union Territories to deal with terrorist activities as per Govt.\r\nGoa Quota seats	Five seats over and above the intake capacity at Mumbai Veterinary College, Mumbai; Four seats at KNP College of Veterinary Science, Shirwal Two seats at College of Veterinary and Animal Science, Parbhani\r\nNRI/FN/PIO/OCI Quota seats	Total 10 seats over and above the intake capacity of B. V. Sc. & A.H.', 'Eligibility\r\nCriteria\r\n\r\nCriteria	Unreserved Category	Reserved Category\r\nXIIth Std. passed in 10+2 pattern or an equivalent Examination ( Physics , Chemistry, Biology or Biotechnology and English)	Minimum 50%	Minimum 47.50%\r\nAge Criteria	Minimum 17 years and should be below 25 years	Minimum 17 years and should be below 25 years (Relaxation of maximum age by 5 year)\r\n\r\nQuota\r\n\r\nUniversity Quota seats	70% seats of University quota at each constituent college shall be filled in as regional quota (R-quota) 30% of the seats of total intake capacity shall be filled as state quota (S-quota)\r\nVCI Quota seats	15% of total intake capacity of each Veterinary College shall be filled in by Veterinary Council of India (VCI), New Delhi through its independent admission procedure.\r\nJ&K and Ladakh UT Quota seats	One seat over and above the intake capacity at each Veterinary College shall be filled from the wards of citizens displaced due to terrorist activities from Jammu & Kashmir Union Territories and Ladakh Union Territories and also from the wards of officers belonging to Indian Administrative Services, Indian Police Services and other officers and staff belonging to military and paramilitary forces transferred to Jammu & Kashmir and Ladakh Union Territories to deal with terrorist activities as per Govt.\r\nGoa Quota seats	Five seats over and above the intake capacity at Mumbai Veterinary College, Mumbai; Four seats at KNP College of Veterinary Science, Shirwal Two seats at College of Veterinary and Animal Science, Parbhani\r\nNRI/FN/PIO/OCI Quota seats	Total 10 seats over and above the intake capacity of B. V. Sc. & A.H.', 'Fee Structure\r\n\r\nApplication Fees (Non-Refundable)\r\nFor Unreserved candidate	Rs. 1000/-\r\nFor Reserved candidate	Rs. 700/-\r\nFor candidate from the states other than Maharashtra	Rs. 1000/-\r\n\r\nMOP-UP Round Fees (Seacurity Deposite Refundable Subject to Certain Condition)\r\nCategory	Amount\r\nGeneral/ OBC/EWS/PIO	Rs. 10000/-\r\nSC/ST/PH/ Transgender	Rs 5000/-\r\n\r\nStray Round Participation Fees\r\nCategory	Amount\r\nGeneral/ OBC/EWS/PIO	Rs. 50000/-\r\nSC/ST/PH/ Transgender	Rs 25000/-', '\r\nProcedure\r\n\r\nFor registration Candidate fills the required details, pays the registration (application) fees online and receives an email/SMS regarding username and password\r\n\r\nThe candidate can login with the login credentials, and completes the filling of application form by uploading original documents, photograph, signature etc.\r\n\r\nOnce all information is completely filled and documents uploaded, the candidate previews the filled form & documents for correctness of data and finally submits the online application form by clicking “submit” link on or before last date. Candidate will receive an email/sms against successful submission of the application form.\r\n\r\nApplication form will be primarily scrutinized and the list of candidates submitting deficient or wrong documents will be displayed on website. Such candidate will be required to upload the indicated documents within due date specified by the University\r\n\r\nProvisional merit list will be displayed on the website www.mafsu.ac.in Candidate will receive an email/ SMS regarding his/ her provisional merit status or can view on www.mafsu.ac.in\r\n\r\nFinal merit list will be displayed on www.mafsu.ac.in. Candidate will receive an email/ sms regarding his/ her final merit status or can view on www.mafsu.ac.in\r\n\r\n\r\nFirst Round of Region Quota admission\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference form For First Round of Region Quota admission\r\n\r\nDisplay of First Round allotment list for Region quota\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 1st round of region quota\r\n\r\nDisplay of allotment list of 1st Round of region quota waiting candidate\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 1st Round of Region Quota waiting list candidate\r\n\r\nLast date for submission of CVC\r\n\r\n\r\nSecond Round of Region Quota admission\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference form For Second Round of Region Quota admission\r\n\r\nDisplay of Second Round allotment list for Region quota\r\n•\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 2nd round of region quota\r\n\r\n\r\nFirst Round of State Quota Admission\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference form For First Round of State Quota admission. (including J&K, Goa State and NRI/FN/PIO quota candidates)\r\n\r\nDisplay of First Round allotment list for State Quota (including list of J & K, Goa State and NRI/FN/PIO quota)\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 1st round of state quota\r\n\r\nDisplay of allotment list of 1st Round of State Quota waiting candidate\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted\r\n\r\n\r\nSecond Round of State Quota Admission\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference Filling option form for Second Round of State Quota\r\n\r\nDisplay of Second Round allotment list for State Quota\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 2nd round of state quota\r\n\r\n\r\nThird Round of (Combine R & S quota)\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference Filling option form for Third Round of (Combine R & S quota)\r\n\r\nDisplay of Third Round allotment list\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 3rd round\r\n\r\nDisplay of allotment list of 3rd Round waiting list candidate\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college for 3rd round waiting\r\n\r\n\r\nSpecial Round of admission\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCandidate fills up the preference Filling option form For Special Round\r\n\r\nDisplay of Special Round allotment list (if vacancy exists including NRI/FN/PIO Quota)\r\n\r\nLast date of reporting at allotted college\r\n\r\nDisplay of waiting list of Special Round\r\n\r\nReporting date (Special Round) for waiting list candidate\r\n', 'What courses are offered at MAFSU? \r\nMAFSU offers undergraduate programs such as the Bachelor of Veterinary Science and Animal Husbandry (B.V.Sc. & A.H.), Bachelor of Fisheries Science (B.F.Sc.), and B.Tech in Dairy Technology, as well as postgraduate programs like Master of Veterinary Science (M.V.Sc.), M.Tech in Dairy Technology, diplomas, and Ph.D. programs.\r\n\r\nWhat is the eligibility for the B.V.Sc. & A.H. degree course at MAFSU? \r\nmust have passed Class 12 (10 + 2) with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Biotechnology and English with a minimum of 50 percent marks for the unreserved category and 47.5 percent for reserved categories. They must also qualify the NEET-UG exam as the admission criterion for this course.\r\n\r\nWhat is the eligibility for the B.F.Sc. degree course?\r\n Candidates must have passed Class 12 (10 + 2) with Physics, Chemistry, Biology, and English, securing at least 50 percent marks for unreserved and 40 percent for reserved categories. Admission to the B.F.Sc. program is based on MHT-CET or equivalent merit criteria.\r\n\r\nHow are students selected for admission to MAFSU programs? \r\nAdmission to undergraduate courses like B.V.Sc. & A.H. is primarily based on NEET-UG merit for veterinary science, while B.F.Sc. and B.Tech dairy technology admissions are based on MHT-CET merit. Postgraduate admissions such as M.V.Sc. require appropriate postgraduate entrance examinations like AIEEA-PG or merit as per the university prospectus.\r\n\r\nWhat is the duration of the B.V.Sc. & A.H. course? \r\nThe Bachelor of Veterinary Science & Animal Husbandry degree typically spans five and a half years, including a compulsory one-year internship after completion of academic coursework.\r\n\r\nWhat is the duration of the B.F.Sc. course? \r\nThe Bachelor of Fisheries Science program generally runs for four academic years, covering classroom instruction and practical training.\r\n\r\nWhat are some general application requirements? \r\nApplicants must apply online only through MAFSU’s official admissions portal, upload all relevant documents such as mark sheets, entrance exam scorecards, and category certificates, and pay the prescribed application fee through the online payment gateway within the scheduled dates specified in the prospectus.\r\n\r\n\r\n', NULL, 7, 1, '2026-01-07 10:39:14', '2026-01-09 07:14:20'),
(49, 'UG', 2, 'all-india-josaa', 'All India JOSAA Process', './assets/images/JOSAA.jpeg ', 'All India JOSAA Process', 'Introduction\r\nJOSAA (Joint Seat Allocation Authority) is a centralized counselling system established by the Ministry of Human Resource Development in India. It facilitates the allocation of seats in 110 institutes, including IITs, NITs, IIITs, and GFTIs, for the academic year 2023. Candidates who have cleared the JEE Main and JEE Advanced exams participate in the online counselling process, where seats are allocated based on merit and candidate preferences. JOSAA aims to streamline the admission process, ensuring fairness, transparency, and convenience for applicants.', 'Eligibility\r\nEligibility Condition\r\n\r\nQualifying Exams:- Candidates must have appeared for the JEE Main and/or JEE Advanced exams in the relevant academic year\r\n\r\nAge Limit:- There is no specific age limit for appearing in JEE Main and JEE Advanced exams. However, candidates should check the age criteria specified by individual institutes for admission\r\n\r\nEducational Qualifications:- Candidates should have passed their 10+2 examination or its equivalent with Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics as compulsory subjects. The minimum aggregate marks required may vary for different institutes and categories\r\n\r\nJEE Main/JEE Advanced Rank:- Candidates must have a valid rank in either JEE Main or JEE Advanced, depending on the institutes they are targeting. The rank obtained in these exams will determine their eligibility for admission and seat allocation through JOSAA.\r\n\r\nCategory:- Reservation policies apply as per the regulations of the Government of India. Candidates belonging to specific categories such as SC/ST/OBC-NCL/PwD may have relaxation in eligibility criteria and seat allocation.\r\n\r\nQuota\r\n\r\nIITs (Indian Institutes of Technology):- For undergraduate courses such as B.Tech around 100% of seats are typically filled through JOSAA counselling based on JEE Advanced ranks.\r\n\r\nNITs (National Institutes of Technology):- For undergraduate courses like B.Tech and B.Arch, approximately 85-90% of seats are usually filled through JOSAA counselling based on JEE Main ranks.\r\n\r\nIIITs (Indian Institutes of Information Technology):- Similar to NITs, around 85-90% of undergraduate engineering seats for courses like B.Tech and B.Arch are typically filled through JOSAA counselling based on JEE Main ranks.\r\n\r\nGFTIs (Other Government Funded Technical Institutes):- Similar to NITs and IIITs, approximately 85-90% of undergraduate engineering seats for courses like B.Tech and B.Arch are usually filled through JOSAA counselling based on JEE Main ranks.', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	Reservation Percentage\r\nScheduled Caste (SC)	15%\r\nScheduled Tribes (ST)	7.5%\r\nOther Backward Classes (NCL)	27%\r\nEWS	10%\r\nPerson with Disability (PwD)	5%', 'Govt: ₹10,000 – ₹1,00,000 | Private: ₹1–5 Lakhs', 'Process Flow\r\n\r\n\r\nRound 2\r\n\r\nEligible candidates for JoSAA Round 2 include those who registered for JoSAA counselling and did not accept a seat in Round 1 or opted for the float or slide options\r\n\r\nIn Round 2, candidates can modify their choice preferences on the JoSAA portal\r\n\r\nSeat allocation is based on updated choices, availability of seats, and candidate ranks\r\n\r\nAfter allocation, candidates must either accept the seat, float it, or withdraw it\r\n\r\nAccepted seats require reporting to reporting centres for document verification and admission confirmation\r\n\r\nFloating seats allow participation in subsequent rounds\r\n\r\nWithdrawing seats forfeits further participation in JoSAA\r\n\r\n\r\nRound 3\r\n\r\nEligible candidates for JoSAA Round 3 include those who registered for JoSAA counselling and did not accept a seat in Round 1 or opted for the float or slide options\r\n\r\nIn Round 3, candidates can modify their choice preferences on the JoSAA portal\r\n\r\nSeat allocation is based on updated choices, availability of seats, and candidate ranks\r\n\r\nAfter allocation, candidates must either accept the seat, float it, or withdraw it\r\n\r\nAccepted seats require reporting to reporting centres for document verification and admission confirmation\r\n\r\nFloating seats allow participation in subsequent rounds\r\n\r\nWithdrawing seats forfeits further participation in JoSAA\r\n\r\nSame process till 6th Round\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCSAB (Central Seat Allocation Board) ROUND\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEligible candidates who did not get allocated a seat in earlier rounds or who want to participate in the special rounds can register at https://csab.nic.in/ and participate\r\n\r\nAvailable seats are allocated based on candidates\' preferences, ranks, and seat availability\r\n\r\nCandidates can accept allocated seats, float them for further rounds, or withdraw if desired\r\n\r\nReporting to reporting centers for document verification and confirmation of admission is required for accepted seats\r\n\r\nThe special rounds provide an opportunity for candidates to secure admission to engineering programs in participating institutes', 'FAQ\r\nI locked my choices but now I would like to make further changes to my choice list. Is that allowed? If yes, how can I exercise the option?\r\nIf you wish to edit your choices after locking but before the choice filling deadline, you can do so by first submitting a request to unlock in the online JoSAA portal. Please refer to Clause 40 for detailed procedure to unlock the choices.\r\n\r\nChoice filling deadline is already over. Am I allowed to make any changes in my choice list at this point?\r\nNo. You will not be allowed to edit your choice list after the deadline for choice filling, i.e. you cannot change the order of your choices OR add any more course in OR delete any course from the choice list after the deadline for choice filling. Please refer to Clause 40 for detailed guidelines.\r\n\r\nI saved my last filled choice list but I forgot to lock them. Now the choice filling deadline is over and I cannot make any further changes. Will this affect the list of choices that will be considered for allocating a seat to me during the JoSAA?\r\nIf you do not lock your choices, last saved choices will be locked automatically upon reaching the deadline for choice filling. The automatically locked choice list will be considered for allocating a seat during JoSAA.\r\n\r\nI got allocated a seat in a certain round of JoSAA for the first time but I am not interested in this seat. I would like to wait for further rounds of JoSAA to possibly get a better seat in my preference order. Do I need to do anything in the current round?\r\nIf you are allocated a seat in a certain round of JoSAA, you need to follow steps for online reporting that include (i) acceptance of the seat, (ii) uploading of documents and (iii) payment of seat acceptance fee. You need to accept the seat and choose an option of Float/Slide if you wish to be considered for a seat of higher preference in any Institute/within the allocated Institute in the subsequent rounds (other than the 6th round). If you fail to complete any of the three steps of online reporting for seat acceptance, your allocated seat will be CANCELLED, and you will no longer be able to participate in the seat allocation process. Please refer to Clause 41 and 42 of JoSAA Business Rules for details of online reporting.\r\n\r\nI was allocated a seat in one of the previous rounds and now I have been allocated another seat of higher preference in my choice list. Can I go back to the seat allotted to me in the previous round?\r\nNo. Once you are allocated a seat of higher preference based on your float/slide option, your accepted seat from the earlier round will be automatically cancelled and you cannot get the previously allotted seat. Please refer to Clause 47 & 48 of JoSAA Business Rules for more details.\r\n\r\nI got allocated a seat of my preference in my choice list in a certain round and I am satisfied about the allotted program. I do not want to participate in further rounds of seat allocation. What should I do to keep the allocated seat?\r\nIf you are satisfied with the allotted seat and do not wish to participate in further rounds of seat allocation, you need to choose the option “Freeze” while accepting the seat and complete all the three steps of online reporting process. Please refer to Clause 48 of JoSAA Business Rules for more details.\r\n\r\nWhat happens if I do not complete all the steps of online reporting during a particular round of JoSAA in which I am allocated a seat for the first time?\r\nYour allocated seat will be CANCELLED, and you will no longer be able to participate in the subsequent rounds of seat allocation process (if any) if you do not complete all the steps of online reporting process including the payment of seat acceptance fee. Please refer to Clauses 41, 42 & 45 of JoSAA Business Rules for more details.\r\n\r\nI was allocated and confirmed a seat in a certain round in an IIT. I have now been allocated another seat of higher preference in my choice list in another IIT. Do I need to report again online?\r\nNo, if you have already completed all the steps of online reporting process in a certain round in an IIT reporting centre and you have been allocated another seat of higher preference in your choice list in another IIT, you don’t have to repeat the online reporting process.\r\n\r\n', NULL, 1, 1, '2026-01-07 10:40:39', '2026-01-09 07:30:42'),
(50, 'UG', 2, 'maharashtra-engineering', 'Maharashtra Engineering Admission Process', './assets/images/MHTCET.jpeg ', 'Maharashtra Engineering Admission Process', 'Introduction\r\nThe Government of Maharashtra has established “ADMISSIONS REGULATING AUTHORITY AND STATE COMMON ENTRANCE TEST CELL“ as per the provisions of the Maharashtra Unaided Private Professional Educational Institutions.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Commissioner of State CET Cell, has been designated as Competent Authority for conducting MHT-CET and selection of candidates for admission to First Year of 4 Year Full Time Under Graduate Professional Degree courses in Agriculture Universities in the State of Maharashtra for the Academic Year Agriculture Universities.\r\n\r\n\r\nGovernment of Maharashtra hereby declares and notifies the additional educational courses of studies of the Agriculture and Animal Husbandry, Dairy Development and Fisheries Department mentioned the schedule appended hereto shall be the Professional Educational Courses for the purpose of said act and specifies that the conditions and the requirements for admissions mentioned respectively against of the schedule shall be the eligibility conditions and requirements for admission to professional Undergraduate Courses B. Sc. (Honours) (Agriculture) / B. Sc. (Honours) (Horticulture) / B. Sc. (Honours) (Forestry) / B. F. Sc. (Fisheries Science)/ B. Tech. (Agriculture Engineering) / B. Tech. (Food Technology)/ B. Sc. (Honours) (Community Science) / B. Tech. (Bio-Technology)/ B. Sc. (Honours) (Agri. Business Management) This CET is mandatory for . This CET is mandatory for admissions in Government, Government Aided and Un-aided private Professional Educational Institutions.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Examination Coordinator (Technical Education), State CET Cell, Mumbai shall act as Nodal Officer for the MHT-CET.', 'Eligibility\r\nEligibility Condition for Maharashtra State Candidature\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Candidate should have qualified MHT-CET\r\n\r\nDomicile free\r\n\r\nEligibility Condition for Other State Candidature (OMS)\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Candidate should have qualified JEE/NEET will also be considered equivalent to MHT-CET for admission\r\n\r\nJammu and Kashmir Migrant Candidates will be considered as OMS candidates\r\n\r\nDomicile free\r\n\r\nEligibility Condition for Minority Candidature\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Candidate should have qualified JEE/NEET will also be considered equivalent to MHT-CET for admission\r\n\r\nThe candidate belonging to a particular Linguistic or Religious Minority Community and belonging to the State of Maharashtra\r\n\r\nDomicile free\r\n\r\nEligibility Condition for Minority Candidature\r\n\r\nProfessional Educational Courses	Eligibility Conditions and Requirements for Admission\r\nFirst year of four-year integrated programme leading to B. Sc. (Honours) Agriculture	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics or Inter Agriculture (with Physics, Chemistry) and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB / PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology / Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four-year integrated Programme leading to B. Sc. (Honours) Horticulture	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics or Inter Agriculture (with Physics, Chemistry) and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB / PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology / Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four year integrated Programme leading to B. Sc. (Honours) Forestry	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Inter Agriculture (with Physics, Chemistry) and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology / Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four year integrated Programme leading to B. Tech. (Agriculture Engineering)	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who has passed qualifying examination without Biology shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four year integrated Programme leading to B. Tech. (Food Technology)	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four year integrated Programme leading to B. Sc. (Honours) Community Science	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB/PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology / Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four year integrated Programme leading to B. Tech. (Biotechnology)	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB/PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have passed qualifying examination without Biology / Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four years integrated Programme leading to B. F. Sc. Degree Course.	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with Physics, Chemistry, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Biology or Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics and English.\r\nObtained score in Common Entrance Test (PCB/PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who has passed qualifying examination without Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective university.\r\nFirst year of four-year integrated Programme leading B. Sc. (Honours) (Agri. Business Management)	\r\nXII Std. (Science) passed in 10+2 pattern from Maharashtra State Board of Higher Secondary Education or an equivalent Examination, with PCB, PCM or PCMB and English.\r\nObtain score in Common Entrance Examination (PCB or PCM) of the respective year conducted by the Competent Authority.\r\nThe candidate who have not offered Biology or Mathematics shall have to complete deficiency courses as prescribed by respective University.\r\n', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	Reservation Percentage\r\nScheduled Castes and Schedule Caste converts to Buddhism (SC)	13%\r\nSchedule Tribes (ST)	7%\r\nVimukta Jati (VJ)/De Notified Tribes(DT) (NT-A)	3%\r\nNomadic Tribes 1 (NT-B)	2.5%\r\nNomadic Tribes 2 (NT-C)	3.5%\r\nNomadic Tribes 3 (NT-D)	2%\r\nOther Backward Classes (OBC)	19%', 'Fees\r\nNon Refundable Registration fee :-    \r\nfor UR/EWS candidates	Rs. 800/-\r\nFor SC/ ST/ OBC/ PwD candidates	Rs. 600/-\r\nNRI / OCI /PIO, Foreign National	Rs. 5000/-\r\n\r\n', 'Registration,\r\nChoice Filling,\r\nSeat Allotment,\r\nDocument Verification,\r\nPhysical Reporting to Colleges\r\nWith Documents & D.D. of Fees\r\n.\r\n\r\nROUND-2 –\r\n  	If any seats remain vacant after the first round of counselling, then the second round is conducted. \r\n	Candidates who did not participate in the first round or did not get a seat in the first round can participate in the second round.\r\nAdditional Round 3 –\r\n	If any seats remain vacant after the second round of counselling, an additional round of counselling may be conducted to fill the vacant seats.\r\n\r\nAfter completing the counselling process, candidates must report to the allotted college to complete the admission formalities and pay the admission fee.\r\n\r\n●	Required Documents-\r\n1.	MHT-CET Admit Card\r\n2.	MHT-CET Scorecard\r\n3.	SSC (Class 10) Marksheet and Passing Certificate\r\n4.	HSC (Class 12) Marksheet and Passing Certificate\r\n5.	School/College Leaving Certificate\r\n6.	Caste Certificate (if applicable)\r\n7.	Domicile Certificate (if applicable)\r\n8.	Non-Creamy Layer Certificate (if applicable)\r\n9.	Aadhar Card\r\n10.	Passport-size Photographs\r\n11.	Passport-size Photographs\r\n\r\n\r\n', '<div><h3>Q1. Is MHT CET compulsory?</h3><p>Yes, MHT CET is required for state engineering colleges.</p></diFAQ for all tabs\r\n●	FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS (FAQ) – \r\nQue 1. -  How to register for MHT CET counselling 2024?\r\nAns- To participate in the MHT CET 2024 counselling, candidates need to register online on the official website mahacet.org. At the time of registration, candidates need to fill all the required details in the form and upload the necessary documents. After registration, Maharashtra CET Cell will release a merit list based on MHT CET score and class 12 marks. All the candidate with their name in the merit list will be required to fill choices of colleges for seat allotment. The allotment of seats will be done on the basis of rank in the MHT CET merit list.\r\n\r\nQue 2. -  I have not appeared in MHT CET 2024 exam. Can I participate in MHT CET counselling 2024?\r\nAns- Candidates who have not appeared in MHT CET exam can participate in the counselling based on their JEE Main score, if appeared. Candidates who did not appeared either in JEE Main or MHT CET can participate in the counselling based on their class 12 percentage.\r\nAdmission in BTech courses in Maharashtra is given on the basis of three exams\r\n●	MHT CET\r\n●	JEE Main\r\n●	Class 12 Marks\r\nA certain number of seats are reserved under Home-State quota and All India quota. All India quota seats are filled on the basis of JEE Main scores while Home-State quota seats are filled on through MHT CET scores. At the end of counselling/seat allotment on the basis of MHT CET and JEE Main, seats that remain vacant are filled on the basis of class 12 marks.\r\nAt the time of registration for MHT CET counselling, candidates need to provide the detail of applying for admission on the basis of JEE Main/MHT CET or class 12.\r\n\r\n\r\n Que 3.- In how many languages MHT CET exam is conducted?\r\nAns- Maharashtra CET Cell conducts MHT CET exam in a total of 3 languages. The languages in which the paper is conducted are Marathi, Urdu, and English. Students can select the language of their choice from the available options while filling out the application form. The language of MHT CET question paper during the exam will be available in a total of 3 languages, English, Urdu and Marathi. The language of paper can be switched among these 3 languages during the exam.\r\n Que 4.- How many rounds are there in MHT CET counselling?\r\nAns- The Maharashtra Common Entrance Test Cell will conduct at total of three rounds counselling and seat allotment process. The exact schedule with the number of rounds will be announced soon on the official website mahacet.org. Currently, the MHT CET counselling registration is open from June 24 to July 3.\r\n\r\nQue 5.- Can I still participate in MHT CET counselling if I do not accept the seat allotted to me?\r\nAns- The process of MHT CET counselling and seat allotment consists of several processes. Once a seat is allotted to a candidate, he/she has the option of “Accept and Freeze” and “Accept and Float”. If a candidate is satisfied with the allotted seat and selects the first option, he/she cannot participate in the next round counselling. If the candidate is not satisfied with the allotted seat, he/she can select the second option trough which he/she can participate in the next round counselling with the current seat.\r\nQue 6-Do we have to pay for every round of Counselling?\r\nAns- Do we have to pay for every round of Counselling?\r\nNO, YOU DON\'T HAVE TO SUBMIT THE REGISTRATION FEES FOR EVERY ROUND IN THE NEET UG COUNSELLING. You only need to pay the registration fee once at the beginning of the counselling process, regardless of how many rounds you participate in.', NULL, 2, 1, '2026-01-07 10:40:39', '2026-01-09 07:33:12');
