(51, 'UG', 2, 'nata-architecture', 'National Aptitude Test in Architecture (NATA)', './assets/images/NATA.jpeg\r\n', 'NATA', 'Introduction\r\nThe Government of Maharashtra, empowered by the Maharashtra Unaided Private Professional Educational Institutions (Regulation of Admissions and Fees) Act, 2015, has issued rules and subsequent amendments to regulate admissions to various professional undergraduate and postgraduate technical courses. These courses include Engineering and Technology, Pharmacy, Architecture, Hotel Management and Catering Technology, as well as Planning, Design, Pharmacy (Practice), Pharm. D. and integrated Master of Engineering and Technology programs. The rules also extend to admissions in Government and Government Aided professional educational institutions. Through Government Resolutions and amendments, these regulations have been enforced and updated periodically. This brochure serves as a comprehensive guide outlining the eligibility criteria, admission rules, and procedures for both first-year and direct second-year admissions in Maharashtra\'s technical professional degree courses. It covers aspects such as the application process, merit list preparation, seat distribution, reservation policies, Centralised Admission Process (CAP) rounds, admissions under Institutional Quota seats, supernumerary seats, fee refund policies, and more. This document aims to provide clarity and transparency to prospective students seeking admission to technical courses in the state of Maharashtra.', 'Eligibility\r\nEligibility Condition for Maharashtra State Candidature\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Candidate should have qualified MHT-CET\r\n\r\nMaharashtra Domiciled\r\n\r\nQualify in an aptitude test in architecture conducted by NTA (NATA)\r\n\r\nPassed 10+2 with Physics, Mathematics, and one of Chemistry/Biology/Technical Vocational subject/Computer Science/Business Studies with at least 45% aggregate marks (40% for Reserved Categories, Economically Weaker Section, and Person with Disability candidates from Maharashtra)\r\nAlternatively, passed 10+3 Diploma Examination with Mathematics and obtained at least 45% aggregate marks (40% for Reserved Categories, Economically Weaker Section, and Person with Disability candidates from Maharashtra).\r\n\r\nEligibility Condition for Deemed University Other State Candidature (OMS)\r\n\r\n\r\nIndian nationals or equivalent status\r\n\r\nQualify in an aptitude test in architecture conducted by NTA (NATA) or CoA (JEE with aptitude test in architecture)\r\n\r\nEligibility Condition for Minority Candidature\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Candidate should have qualified NATA will also be considered equivalent to MHT-CET for admission\r\n\r\nThe candidate belonging to a particular Linguistic or Religious Minority Community and belonging to the State of Maharashtra\r\n\r\nDomicile free\r\n', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	Reservation Percentage\r\nSchedule Caste and Schedule Caste converted to Buddhism (SC)	13%\r\nSchedule Tribe (ST)	7%\r\nVimukta Jati (VJ)/De Notified Tribes(DT) (NT-A)	3%\r\nNomadic Tribes 1 (NT-B)	2.5%\r\nNomadic Tribes 2 (NT-C)	3.5%\r\nNomadic Tribes 3 (NT-D)	2%\r\nOther Backward Classes (OBC)	19%', 'Fees\r\nNon-Refundable Registration fee: -    \r\nfor UR/EWS candidates	Rs. 800/-\r\nFor SC/ ST/ OBC/ PwD candidates	Rs. 600/-\r\nNRI / OCI /PIO, Foreign National	Rs. 5000/-\r\n\r\n', '●	Process Flow: \r\n \r\n\r\nROUND-2 –\r\n  	If any seats remain vacant after the first round of counselling, then the second round is conducted. \r\n	Candidates who did not participate in the first round or did not get a seat in the first round can participate in the second round.\r\nAdditional Round 3 –\r\n	If any seats remain vacant after the second round of counselling, an additional round of counselling may be conducted to fill the vacant seats.\r\nAfter completing the counselling process, candidates must report to the allotted college to complete the admission formalities and pay the admission fee.\r\n\r\n•	Required Documents-\r\n1.	MHT-CET Admit Card\r\n2.	MHT-CET Scorecard\r\n3.	NATA Score Card\r\n4.	SSC (Class 10) Marksheet and Passing Certificate\r\n5.	HSC (Class 12) Marksheet and Passing Certificate\r\n6.	School/College Leaving Certificate\r\n7.	Caste Certificate (if applicable)\r\n8.	Caste Validity (if applicable)\r\n9.	Domicile Certificate\r\n10.	Non-Creamy Layer Certificate (if applicable)\r\n11.	Aadhar Card\r\n12.	Passport-size Photographs\r\n13.	Receipt of Counselling Registration and Application Fee Payment\r\n\r\n', 'FAQ\r\nHow can I apply for architecture admission in Maharashtra?\r\nCandidates can apply online through the https://cetcell.mahacet.org/admissions/ website as per the notified schedule. They need to fill the application form, pay the application fee (if applicable), and upload necessary documents.\r\n\r\nWhat are the eligibility criteria for architecture admission in Maharashtra?\r\nEligibility criteria include passing 10+2 with Physics, Mathematics, and one of Chemistry/Biology/Technical Vocational subjects with at least 45% aggregate marks (40% for reserved categories). Alternatively, candidates with a 10+3 Diploma with Mathematics are eligible.\r\n\r\nWhat is the role of the Centralised Admission Process (CAP) in architecture admission?\r\nCAP facilitates the admission process by centralizing seat allocation and counselling. It includes stages such as document verification, display of merit lists, option form filling, provisional allotment, and seat acceptance.\r\n\r\nWhat documents are required for architecture admission in Maharashtra?\r\nDocuments such as SSC/HSC/Diploma mark sheets, domicile certificate (if applicable), caste certificate (if applicable), NATA/JEE scorecard, and photo ID proof are typically required for verification.\r\n\r\nHow many CAP rounds are conducted for architecture admission?\r\nMultiple CAP rounds are conducted depending on the availability of seats. Candidates can participate in subsequent rounds based on their preference and availability of seats.\r\n\r\nHow can I check the provisional merit list and final merit lists?\r\nProvisional and final merit lists are displayed on the official website. Candidates can check their names and report any discrepancies within the specified period.\r\n\r\nWhat is the procedure for seat acceptance after allotment?\r\nCandidates need to report to the Admission Reporting Centre (ARC), accept the offered seat, and complete any required documentation. They must then report to the allotted institute for admission.\r\n\r\nIs there any provision for grievance redressal during the admission process?\r\nYes, candidates can submit grievances regarding provisional merit lists or allotments within the specified period through the method prescribed by the Competent Authority.\r\n\r\nWhat happens if I miss the deadlines during the admission process?\r\nMissing deadlines may result in disqualification from the admission process. It\'s essential to adhere to the prescribed timelines to ensure smooth participation in CAP rounds and seat allotment.', NULL, 3, 1, '2026-01-07 10:40:39', '2026-01-09 07:35:28'),
(52, 'UG', 3, 'iiser', 'IISER Admission Process', './assets/images/IISER.jpeg', 'IISER', 'Indian Institutes of Science Education and Research (IISERs) was established by the\r\nGovernment of India at Berhampur, Bhopal, Kolkata, Mohali, Pune, Thiruvananthapuram,\r\nand Tirupati to integrate and promote interdisciplinary science education and research.\r\nOver the years, the IISERs have been successfully attracting talented young minds. An\r\noverarching goal of the IISERs is to enable students to shape the nation by inventing and\r\nimplementing sustainable solutions for societal problems through research in science. This\r\nis being achieved by our faculty of international repute together with bright students. In a\r\nshort span of time, the IISERs have generated an incredible amount of intellectual property\r\nin the form of publications and patents.', 'Eligibility Criteria:-\r\n● Applicants must be Indian nationals or PIO or OCI in order to apply through KVPY or JEE\r\n(Advanced) or IAT channels. Candidates who are NOT Indian nationals or PIO or OCI can\r\napply for admission only through the JEE (Advanced) channel.\r\n● Candidates must have passed Class XII (or equivalent) exam with science stream in 2022\r\nor 2023 from any board recognized by Council of Boards of School Education in India\r\nCOBSE.\r\n● Candidates must have taken at least three subjects among Biology, Chemistry,\r\nMathematics and Physics during their Class XII (or equivalent) exam.\r\n● Candidates belonging to SC/ST/PwD should have scored a minimum of 55% marks in\r\naggregate or equivalent grade in their Class XII (or equivalent) exam. Candidates\r\nbelonging to other categories should have scored a minimum of 60% marks in aggregate\r\nor equivalent grade in their Class XII (or equivalent) exam.\r\nNOTE:\r\nIn view of the clarification from The Jammu and Kashmir Board of School Education\r\n(JKBOSE) that the Class 12 Annual Regular Examination conducted by JKBOSE in December 2021 in the case of candidates of Kashmir division/Winter Zones areas of Jammu division and\r\nU.T. of Ladakh is equivalent to the Class 12 Annual Regular Examination conducted by\r\nJKBOSE in the months of March-April 2022 in the case of candidates of Summer Zone areas\r\nof Jammu division, the following has been decided:\r\n1. The students of Kashmir division/Winter Zones areas of Jammu division and U.T. of\r\nLadakh who took the class 12 Annual regular Examination conducted by JKBOSE in\r\nDecember 2021 are eligible to apply to the BSMS and BS courses in the 2023 admission\r\ncycle provided they satisfy all the other eligibility criteria.\r\n2. During the application process, these students need to pick 2022 as their year of passing\r\nclass 12 examination.', 'Reservation of Seats:-\r\n Reservation policies as mandated by Govt. of India will apply.\r\nScheduled Caste (SC)   15% of seats.\r\nScheduled Tribe (ST)   7.5% of seats.\r\nOther Backward Classes belonging to the Non-Creamy Layer(OBC-NCL)  27% of seats.\r\nPersons with Disability (PwD) with at least 40% impairment  5% of seats\r\n(supernumerary).\r\n Kashmiri Migrants  3 seats per IISER (supernumerary).\r\n Economically Weaker Section(EWS)  up to 10% (as per Government of India Rules).\r\nNote that the EWS/OBC-NCL certificate should have been issued on or after 1 April 2023.', 'Online Application and Fee:-\r\n➢ Application Portal – Candidates must apply through the online application portal at\r\n(www.iiseradmission.in). Applications can be submitted only through the online portal\r\nwhere detailed instructions will be provided.\r\nFor online application Indian Institutes of Science Education\r\nand Research (iiseradmission.in)\r\nOnline application begins (IAT-2023) April 15, 2023 (Saturday)\r\nOnline application closes (IAT-2023) May 25, 2023 (Thursday)\r\n➢ Application fee –\r\n● Rs. 2,000/- for candidates applying under General, EWS and OBC-NCL categories.\r\n● Rs.1,000/- for candidates applying under persons with disabilities, persons registered as\r\nKashmiri migrants and SC/ST category.\r\n● Rs 8500 for foreign nationals.\r\n● Application fee is non-refundable.', 'Admission Process:-\r\na. Entire counselling process will be conducted online. There is no need for the candidates\r\nto visit any IISER in-person during the counselling process.\r\nb. Candidates can check if they received admission offers by logging into their application\r\nportal.\r\nc. Admission offers to any candidate will be given strictly based on the following factors:\r\nIISERs (2023) – Information Brochure\r\n18\r\n● seat availability at each IISER in the current allocation round,\r\n● IAT rank obtained by the candidate OR JEE/KVPY rank (as applicable),\r\n● IISER preferences given by the candidate, and\r\n● the category to which the candidate belongs.\r\nd. If a candidate receives an admission offer, he/she can either choose to accept the seat OR\r\nreject it. If a candidate rejects the offered seat or if no action is taken by the candidate\r\nbefore the deadline, then the candidate will not be able to participate in further rounds of\r\ncounselling.\r\ne. If a candidate receives an offer, then to accept the seat offered, the student must pay a seat\r\nacceptance fee through online mode before the prescribed deadline. If the seat acceptance\r\nfee is not paid, the candidate will not be considered for admission in subsequent allocation\r\nrounds.\r\nf. After accepting the offer and paying seat acceptance fee, the candidate can exercise two\r\noptions:\r\n● Candidate can FREEZE the seat (they will not participate in further rounds of\r\ncounselling),\r\n● Candidate can FLOAT (they will participate in further rounds of counselling to get\r\ntheir higher preferences). The FLOAT option is activated by default for those who\r\npay the seat acceptance fee.\r\ng. A student who has chosen to FLOAT will be again considered for seat allocation in the\r\nnext round. If they are eligible to secure a seat in an IISER that is higher in their preference\r\nlist than the currently accepted one, they will be offered that seat.\r\nh. If seats in preferred IISERs are filled, then candidate will not be considered in further\r\nrounds of counselling. For example, if a candidate had given only two preferences as\r\nIISER-X and IISER-Y, and if the seats in these IISERs are filled, then the candidate will\r\nnot be considered for seat allocation anymore. This process happens even if the student\r\nhas not been allocated any seat in previous counselling rounds.\r\ni. Admission offers given are provisional. They will be confirmed only after the candidates\r\nreport at the IISER where they have secured admission and provide all the required\r\ndocuments in original.\r\nIISERs (2023) – Information Brochure\r\n19\r\nj. Requests for extension of date or time for seat acceptance will not be entertained under\r\nany circumstances. Published deadlines will be strictly followed.\r\nk. All the announcements related to the admission process will appear on this website.\r\nCandidates must follow this website for any updates.', '\r\nWhat is the IISER Admission Process?\r\n The Indian Institutes of Science Education and Research (IISERs) admit students into undergraduate programmes such as the five‑year BS‑MS (Dual Degree) and certain BS programmes. For the current year, admissions are conducted through the **IISER Aptitude Test (IAT)**, which is a computer‑based entrance examination that candidates must appear for in order to be considered for admission to IISERs across India. ([iiserpune.ac.in][1])\r\n\r\nWho can apply for IISER admissions? Candidates who have passed their Class XII (or equivalent) examination in the science stream in the relevant years are eligible to apply. Applicants must have studied at least three subjects among Biology, Chemistry, Mathematics, and Physics in Class XII to be eligible for the IISER Aptitude Test. Applicants can include Indian nationals, OCI/PIO card holders, and foreign nationals (foreign applicants may need to provide equivalence certificates). ([iiseradmission.in][2])\r\n\r\nWhat are the academic requirements for IISER admission? \r\nStudents must have completed Class XII (or equivalent) from a board recognised by the Council of Boards of School Education (COBSE) in India. They should have taken a science stream with subjects including Physics, Chemistry, Biology, and/or Mathematics. Minimum percentage requirements in Class XII may be specified for eligibility as detailed on the official admissions portal. ([iiseradmission.in][2])\r\n\r\nHow is the IISER Aptitude Test (IAT) conducted? \r\nThe IISER Aptitude Test is a computer‑based test administered nationally at designated centres. This test is the exclusive admission test for most IISER undergraduate programmes, with admissions determined by candidates’ performance in the IAT and their programme preferences. ([iiseradmission.in][3])\r\n\r\nWhat happens after the IAT exam? \r\nAfter the IAT is conducted, the results and scorecards are published on the official IISER admissions portal. Candidates whose scores meet the required cut‑offs and merit criteria are considered for seat allocation through the online admissions process. ([The Economic Times][4])\r\n\r\nHow does the counselling and seat allocation process work? \r\nThe entire admissions counselling process is conducted online through the IISER admissions portal. Candidates log in to the portal to check admission offers based on factors such as their IAT rank, programme preferences, category, and seat availability. Candidates can accept or reject offers before the deadline. Accepted offers require payment of a Seat Acceptance Fee (SAF). Candidates may choose to freeze (retain) a seat or float (remain eligible for higher preference seats in subsequent rounds). ([iiseradmission.in][5])\r\n\r\nIs there any interview or personal round? For standard undergraduate admissions via the IAT, there is no interview or personal round; admissions are solely based on the entrance test score, preferences, and online allocation process. ([Reddit][6])\r\n\r\nAre there other channels for IISER admission? \r\nIn the past, admission channels such as the Kishore Vaigyanik Protsahan Yojana (KVPY) and JEE Advanced scores were used for IISER admissions. However, for the most recent admissions cycle, IISER admissions are conducted exclusively through the IISER Aptitude Test for most programmes. ([iiserpune.ac.in][1])\r\n\r\nDo international students have a separate process? \r\nInternational applicants can apply through the IISER Aptitude Test or via designated international admission channels where available, and may need to provide additional documents such as equivalence certificates. ([iiseradmission.in][2])\r\n\r\nWhat programmes are offered through the IISER Admission Process? \r\nIISERs offer the five‑year BS‑MS (Dual Degree) programmes across all institutes, and some IISERs also offer four‑year BS degrees in specific disciplines such as Economics or related sciences. ([dair.iiserb.ac.in][7])\r\n', NULL, 1, 1, '2026-01-07 10:41:20', '2026-01-09 07:36:38'),
(53, 'UG', 3, 'niser-nest', 'NISER-NEST Admission Process', './assets/images/NISER.jpeg', 'NISER-NEST', 'The National Entrance Screening Test or NEST is a compulsory online/computer based test\r\nfor admission to the five year Integrated MSc programme in Biology, Chemistry,\r\nMathematics, and Physics, at the National Institute of Science Education and Research\r\n(NISER), Bhubaneswar and University of Mumbai – Department of Atomic Energy Centre\r\nfor Excellence in Basic Sciences (UM–DAE CEBS), Mumbai.', 'Eligibility criteria summary: a candidate becomes eligible for the programme when\r\nhe/she satisfies all the four criteria stated below:\r\n(a) Secures a position in the NEST merit list. Please refer to page 12 of this document for\r\nthe rules of merit list preparation.\r\n(b) Passed the XII standard board examination in the science stream in the years 2021\r\nor 2022 or has appeared in 2023 from any recognised Higher Secondary Education Board\r\nin India.\r\n(c) Secures at least 60% in aggregate in the XII standard board examination. The\r\nrequirement for SC/ST/Divyangjan candidates is 55%.\r\n(d) Born on or after August 01, 2003. The age limit is relaxed by five years for\r\nSC/ST/Divyangjan students.', ' Category                               Percentage of Reservation Key Conditions                                                                                                                       |OBC – Non Creamy Layer (OBC–NCL) | 27%                       Must be listed in Central OBC list. Valid OBC-NCL certificate required at admission. Creamy layer candidates are treated as General. \r\nEconomically Weaker Section (EWS) As per GoI norms           Applicable under **General-EWS category for CEBS only.                                                                             \r\nScheduled Caste (SC)         15%                       Caste must be listed in official GoI SC list. Valid certificate mandatory.                                                           Scheduled Tribe (ST)        7.5%                      | Tribe must be listed in official GoI ST list. Valid certificate mandatory.                                                           \r\nGeneral                          Remaining seats            Includes OBC creamy layer & candidates not eligible for reservation.                                                                 \r\n', '\r\n 1. NEST Application (Entrance Exam) Fee\r\n\r\nGeneral / OBC (Male)  ₹1,400\r\nAll Female Candidates  ₹700\r\nSC / ST / Divyangjan  ₹700\r\n', 'To apply for NEST 2023, candidates must fill out the online application form through\r\nwww.nestexam.in on or after February 27, 2023. Candidates are strongly advised to read\r\nthrough the detailed online application procedure available on the website (click on\r\n\'How to Apply online\'). The online application process closes on May 17, 2023 (midnight).\r\nApplications can be submitted only through the NEST 2023 website. There is no other mode\r\nof application submission. Login credentials for logging into application submission and\r\nfee payment portals will be provided upon online registration.\r\nApplication Fee: The application fee for the male candidates of the General and OBC\r\ncategories is 1,200/–. The application fee for candidates in the SC/ST/Divyangjan\r\ncategories and all female candidates is 600/–. Payments can be made using credit\r\ncard/debit card/net–banking through an online payment gateway. Please use\r\nMastercard/Visa/RuPay cards only.\r\nCandidates need not send any document to the NEST office during the entire application\r\nprocess.\r\nPlease refer to the instruction sheet (the \'How to Apply Online’ tab on www.nestexam.in)\r\nfor details regarding the application process.\r\nAdmit card: The admit card for NEST 2023 will be available for downloading from June 12,\r\n2023. Admit cards will NOT be dispatched to any applicant. Applicants must download\r\ntheir admit cards from the NEST website (after login). The download link will be available\r\nonly till the day of the examination.', '\r\nWhat is the NISER‑NEST admission process? Admission to the five‑year Integrated MSc programme at the National Institute of Science Education and Research (NISER), Bhubaneswar and the University of Mumbai – Department of Atomic Energy Centre for Excellence in Basic Sciences (UM‑DAE CEBS), Mumbai is through a national computer‑based test called the **National Entrance Screening Test (NEST)**. Candidates who qualify the NEST exam are ranked on a merit list, and admissions are offered strictly based on this merit list and eligibility criteria. ([Nest Exam][1])\r\n\r\nWho is eligible to appear in the NEST exam? \r\nTo be eligible for NEST, candidates should have passed or be appearing for the Class XII board examination in the science stream (with at least three subjects among Biology, Chemistry, Mathematics, and Physics) from a recognised board. They must secure a **minimum of 60 % aggregate marks** in Class XII (55 % for SC/ST/Divyangjan categories) and must have their final results by the time of admission. There is **no upper age limit** to appear in NEST. ([Nest Exam][2])\r\n\r\nHow do I apply for the NEST exam? Candidates must fill out the **online application form** available on the official NEST website (nestexam.in), complete registration, provide all required personal and academic information, upload documents, and pay the examination fee before the deadline specified in the information brochure. ([Nest Exam][3])\r\n\r\nWhat happens after I take the NEST exam? After taking the exam, candidates receive a **scorecard** and are placed on a **merit list** based on their performance in NEST. Admission offers for the Integrated MSc programme are made from this merit list, and candidates may receive emails or notifications guiding them on how to proceed with accepting admission. ([The Times of India][4])\r\n\r\nHow is the admission offer finalised? Once a candidate is selected based on the merit list, they need to **submit an Expression of Interest (EOI)** or follow instructions given by NISER to confirm their intention to join the programme. Candidates must report in person to the NISER campus on the scheduled date for **document verification, admission confirmation, and orientation**. If they fail to report by the given deadline, their seat may be forfeited. ([NISER][5])\r\n\r\nWhat documents are required for admission at NISER? \r\nCandidates admitted to NISER must bring documents such as the printed NEST application/admission form, NEST scorecard, Aadhaar card (original and photocopy), Class 10 and 12 mark sheets and certificates, school leaving certificate, valid caste or disability certificate if applicable, and other specified documents on the day of reporting. ([NISER][5])\r\n\r\nIs there counselling similar to other exams? \r\nThe NEST process does not have a typical multi‑round counselling like some other entrance exams. Instead, candidates who qualify and are on the merit list need to respond to the **admission invitations**, submit required expressions of interest, and complete the reporting and verification process as per instructions from NISER or CEBS. ([Shiksha][6])\r\n\r\nCan I appear for NEST if I am a dropper or older candidate? \r\nYes, there is **no age limit** for appearing in the NEST exam or for admission to the Integrated MSc programme at NISER or CEBS, provided you meet the other eligibility criteria such as passing Class XII in the required years and securing the minimum aggregate marks. ([Nest Exam][2])\r\n', NULL, 2, 1, '2026-01-07 10:41:20', '2026-01-09 07:37:37'),
(54, 'UG', 3, 'iisc', 'IISC Admission Process', './assets/images/IISC.jpeg', 'IISC', 'Introduction\r\n\r\nThe Indian Institute of Science (IISc), Bengaluru, is a premier institution of national importance dedicated to excellence in higher education and advanced research in Pure Science disciplines. Established with the objective of promoting scientific inquiry and innovation, IISc has consistently maintained high academic standards and global recognition.\r\n\r\nAdmissions to Pure Science programmes at IISc are conducted through nationally recognized entrance examinations to ensure transparency, fairness, and merit-based selection. Candidates are shortlisted strictly on the basis of their performance in the prescribed entrance tests, academic credentials, and eligibility criteria defined by the institute.\r\n\r\nIISc follows the reservation policies and admission norms prescribed by the Government of India for all its academic programmes. The institute is committed to providing equal opportunities to students from diverse social and economic backgrounds while maintaining academic excellence.\r\n\r\nThe admission process is carried out in a systematic and transparent manner, ensuring that only eligible and deserving candidates are admitted. All admissions are subject to verification of documents, fulfillment of eligibility requirements, and compliance with institutional and government regulations.', 'Eligibility Criteria\r\n\r\nCandidates must possess a qualifying degree from a recognized university or institution as specified by IISc.\r\n\r\nThe qualifying degree should meet the minimum academic performance requirements prescribed for the respective programme.\r\n\r\nEligibility conditions may vary depending on the programme, department, and discipline.\r\n\r\nA valid national-level entrance examination score such as GATE, NET JRF, or GPAT is required, as applicable.\r\n\r\nOnly entrance test scores obtained in the relevant examination cycle will be considered.\r\n\r\nFinal-year students may apply, provided they complete all degree requirements before the date of admission.\r\n\r\nCandidates must submit proof of eligibility and required documents within the stipulated time.\r\n\r\nApplicants belonging to reserved categories must satisfy the eligibility criteria applicable to their category.\r\n\r\nValid category certificates must be produced at the time of admission for claiming reservation benefits.\r\n\r\nAdmission is subject to verification of academic records and eligibility conditions by IISc.\r\n\r\nIISc reserves the right to cancel admission if any information provided by the candidate is found to be incorrect or incomplete.', 'Category                                            Reservation     \r\nScheduled Caste (SC)                                15% of total seats  \r\nScheduled Tribe (ST)                                7.5% of total seats \r\nOther Backward Classes – Non-Creamy Layer (OBC-NCL)  27% of total seats  \r\nEconomically Weaker Section (EWS)                    10% of total seats  \r\nGeneral (Unreserved)                               Remaining seats     \r\n', 'Category   Tuition Fee (₹)    Other Fees (₹)  Total per Semester (₹) General  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n          10,000    3,700       13,700            \r\nOBC-NCL             10,000           3,700           13,700            \r\nEWS                 10,000          3,700           13,700           \r\nSC          Nil    3,700          3,700            \r\nST                 Nil       3,700            3,700              \r\nDivyangjan (PwD)  As per category  As per category   As per category      \r\n', 'Process Description                                                                                                                                   Step 1  \r\nCandidates appear for national-level entrance examinations such as JEE Advanced, JEE Main, NEET (UG), or other approved channels as notified by IISc.\r\nStep 2   \r\nEligible candidates apply online through the official IISc Undergraduate Admissions portal within the specified application window.                   \r\nStep 3  \r\nApplicants select the applicable admission channel(s) and submit academic, examination, and personal details along with required documents.           \r\nStep 4  \r\nIISc prepares separate merit lists for each admission channel based on ranks obtained in the respective examinations.                                 \r\nStep 5 \r\n Seats are allocated strictly on the basis of merit, availability of seats, and Government of India reservation norms.                                 Step 6  \r\n Shortlisted candidates are issued provisional admission offers through the official admission portal.                                                 Step 7  \r\n Selected candidates must accept the offer within the given deadline and pay the prescribed admission fee online.                                      \r\nStep 8 \r\nCandidates upload category certificates, academic records, and other required documents for verification.                                             \r\nStep 9  \r\n After successful verification, candidates report to IISc on the specified date to complete admission formalities.                                     \r\nStep 10 \r\n Failure to complete any step within the prescribed timeline may result in cancellation of the admission offer.                                        \r\n', '\r\nWhat is the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) admission process? \r\nThe Indian Institute of Science (IISc), Bangalore offers admissions to a range of programmes including undergraduate (such as the four‑year Bachelor of Science (Research) programme), postgraduate course programmes (like M.Sc., M.Tech.), research programmes (Ph.D./M.Tech Research) and other specialised degrees. Prospective students must check eligibility criteria and submit their applications through the **online admissions portal** for each programme. ([Indian Institute of Science][1])\r\n\r\nWho can apply for undergraduate programmes at IISc?\r\n Candidates who have passed or are appearing in the Class XII (or equivalent) examination in the relevant years and meet the subject and eligibility criteria for the specific programme can apply for undergraduate programmes such as the Bachelor of Science (Research). The online application for these programmes is typically open during a specified application window on the admissions website. ([IISc UG][2])\r\n\r\nHow are admissions conducted for the undergraduate B.Sc. research programme? Admission to the four‑year Bachelor of Science (Research) programme at IISc is done through the online admissions portal. Candidates must complete the online application within the given window and provide required information as specified. The selection may involve criteria such as performance in qualifiers like national entrance tests or merit, depending on the programme’s eligibility requirements. ([IISc UG][2])\r\n\r\nWhat eligibility is required for postgraduate and research programmes?\r\n For postgraduate course programmes (such as M.Sc., M.Tech., M.Des., M.Mgt.), candidates must have a relevant qualifying degree and a valid score in national entrance tests like **GATE, JAM, CAT, CEED** as applicable to the specific programme. For research programmes (such as Ph.D. or M.Tech Research), candidates typically need a qualifying degree in the relevant discipline and valid entrance test scores such as **GATE or NET JRF** where specified, along with meeting other criteria detailed by the institute. ([Indian Institute of Science][3])\r\n\r\nHow do candidates submit their applications? \r\nApplicants must first register on the **IISc Online Admissions Portal** by creating an account with their name, date of birth, and email address. After confirming their email, they can log in to fill out the application form, enter personal and academic details, upload necessary documents, declare entrance test scores, and pay the application fee online. Separate applications are required for different programmes, and incomplete forms may be rejected. ([Indian Institute of Science][1])\r\n\r\nWhat tests or exams are considered for IISc admissions? \r\nDepending on the programme, admissions may consider national level exams such as **GATE** for M.Tech, **JAM** for M.Sc., **CEED** for design, **CAT/GMAT** for management, or other relevant scores. Some programmes may also have interviews or written tests as part of the selection process along with the entrance test scores. ([Indian Institute of Science][4])\r\n\r\nWhat documents and details are required during application? \r\nApplicants must provide details of their academic qualifications (like class 10, 12, UG and PG marks), entrance test details, category certificates if applicable, identification information, and other documents specified in the application instructions. Results for some national entrance tests can be updated later through the admissions portal within a specified timeframe after results are declared. ([Indian Institute of Science][1])\r\n\r\nIs there a fee for applying to IISc programmes?\r\n Yes, candidates must pay an application fee online at the time of submission. The fee varies by category (for example, general/OBC/EWS, SC/ST/PwD, sponsored candidates), and payment must be completed for the application to be considered. ([Indian Institute of Science][1])\r\n\r\nWhat happens after submission of the application? \r\nAfter applying, candidates should monitor their application status on the admissions portal, ensure any required updates (like entrance test scores) are submitted, and follow any further instructions provided by IISc for selection, counselling (if applicable), offer letters, or final admission confirmations. ([Indian Institute of Science][4])\r\n', NULL, 3, 1, '2026-01-07 10:41:20', '2026-01-09 07:38:35'),
(56, 'PG', 2, 'Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering', 'Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering', './assets/images/gate_logo.png', 'Engineering icon', 'The Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering (GATE) is a national-level examination in India that tests the comprehensive understanding of various undergraduate subjects in engineering, technology, architecture, and science. It is primarily used for admission to postgraduate programs (M.E., M.Tech, M.Arch, Ph.D.) in Indian institutes like IITs, NITs, and other prestigious universities.\r\n\r\nGATE scores are also widely used by public sector undertakings (PSUs) for recruitment of engineers in technical roles. The exam evaluates candidates on subject knowledge, analytical skills, and problem-solving abilities.\r\n\r\nKey Highlights:\r\n\r\nConducted jointly by the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) and seven IITs on a rotational basis.\r\n\r\nCovers multiple streams like Civil, Mechanical, Electrical, Computer Science, Electronics, Chemical, etc.\r\n\r\nScores are valid for 3 years for admissions and recruitment purposes.\r\n\r\nThe exam is online (Computer Based Test) and includes multiple-choice questions (MCQs) and numerical answer type questions (NAT).', 'Eligibility Criteria      Details                                                                                                                                                                                                          Educational Qualification \r\ndegree in Engineering/Technology (B.E./B.Tech/B.Arch) <br> - Master’s degree in Science/Mathematics/Statistics/Computer Applications Final-year students of eligible programs can also apply \r\nAge Limit                  No age limit                                                                                                                                                                                                     Nationality                Indian nationals and foreign nationals from Nepal, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, UAE, Ethiopia, Singapore                                                                                                               \r\nYear of Passing            Already passed or in the final year of the qualifying program                                                                                                                                                     Documents Required        Educational certificates and valid identity proof                                                                                                                                                                ', 'Category / Reservation Type       Percentage / Details                                             SC (Scheduled Caste)               15%                                                              ST (Scheduled Tribe)               7.5%                                                             \r\nOBC (Other Backward Classes)      27% (Non-Creamy Layer, as per government rules)                  \r\n EWS (Economically Weaker Section)  10%                                                              \r\nGeneral / Unreserved               Remaining seats                                                 PwD (Persons with Disability)      5% horizontal reservation across all categories                  \r\nWomen Candidates                   As per applicable rules in the institution/exam authority        Foreign / NRI Quota               Separate seats with specific eligibility and fees, if applicable ', 'Name of the Course           State Quota Seats Institute / All India Quota Seats  Both State & Institute Quota \r\n\r\n MBBS, BDS, BAMS, BHMS & BUMS Rs. 1,000/-       Rs. 5,000/-                        Rs. 6,000/-                  \r\nBPTh, BOTH, BASLP & BP&O     Rs. 1,000/-       Rs. 1,000/-                       Rs. 1,000/-                \r\n', 'Process Flow – All India Ayush NEET PG (AIAP PG)\r\n\r\nQualify NEET PG\r\n\r\nCandidate must have a valid NEET PG score to be eligible for counselling.\r\n\r\nOnline Registration\r\n\r\nRegister on the All India Ayush PG portal.\r\n\r\nPay the application/registration fee.\r\n\r\nDocument Verification\r\n\r\nUpload/submit required documents:\r\n\r\nBachelor’s degree in Ayush (BAMS/BHMS/BUMS/BPTh/BPT)\r\n\r\nInternship completion certificate\r\n\r\nNEET PG score card\r\n\r\nCategory / reservation certificates\r\n\r\nChoice Filling and Locking\r\n\r\nSelect preferred colleges and courses online.\r\n\r\nLock choices before the deadline.\r\n\r\nSeat Allotment\r\n\r\nSeats allocated based on merit (NEET PG rank), reservation category, and choices submitted.\r\n\r\nReporting to Allotted College\r\n\r\nPay tuition and security fees (if applicable).\r\n\r\nComplete admission formalities and join the college.\r\n\r\nMop-up / Stray Vacancy Rounds\r\n\r\nConducted if any seats remain vacant after the main counselling rounds.', 'What is the Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering (GATE)? \r\nThe Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering (GATE) is a national-level examination conducted jointly by the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) and seven Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) on behalf of the National Coordination Board – GATE. It evaluates the comprehensive understanding of candidates in undergraduate-level engineering, technology, architecture, and science subjects. The exam is primarily used for admissions to postgraduate programs (such as M.E., M.Tech., M.Arch., and Ph.D.) and for recruitment by certain public sector companies in India.\r\n\r\nWho can appear for GATE?\r\n Candidates who have completed or are in the final year of a qualifying undergraduate degree in Engineering/Technology, Architecture, Science, or related fields are eligible to appear for GATE. There is no age limit, and candidates from India as well as international applicants from countries like Bangladesh, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Ethiopia, and Singapore can also apply.\r\n\r\nHow do I apply for GATE?\r\n Candidates must register online through the official GATE website (gate.iitb.ac.in or the respective organizing IIT/IISc portal). The online application involves creating a login ID, entering personal and academic details, uploading scanned copies of photograph and signature, and paying the application fee. Incomplete applications are rejected, so all details must be carefully filled.\r\n\r\nWhat is the structure of the GATE exam? GATE is a **computer-based test (CBT)** consisting of multiple-choice questions (MCQs), multiple-select questions (MSQs), and numerical answer type (NAT) questions. The exam duration is **3 hours**, and the total marks are 100. It tests candidates on **General Aptitude** as well as their respective subject knowledge in the chosen paper/discipline.\r\n\r\nHow are GATE scores used? \r\nGATE scores are primarily used for admission to postgraduate programs such as M.Tech., M.E., M.Arch., and direct Ph.D. programs in IITs, NITs, IISc, and other reputed institutes. Certain public sector undertakings (PSUs) also use GATE scores for recruitment of engineers. The GATE score is valid for **three years** from the date of the result announcement.\r\n\r\nWhat documents are required for GATE application? \r\nCandidates need to submit scanned copies of their **photograph, signature, and qualifying degree certificate or mark sheet**. International candidates may need additional identification documents. During admission or recruitment using GATE scores, candidates may be required to provide class 10, class 12, and undergraduate degree certificates for verification.\r\n\r\nHow is the GATE exam conducted? GATE is conducted **once a year**, usually in February, in multiple sessions across various cities in India and selected international locations. Candidates are assigned a session and center during the application process. The exam is computer-based and proctored.\r\n\r\nWhat happens after the GATE exam? \r\nAfter the exam, results are declared on the official GATE portal. Candidates can download their scorecards online. Admission to postgraduate programs or recruitment by PSUs is then conducted based on the GATE score, rank, category, and institute-specific criteria.\r\n\r\nAre there multiple papers in GATE?\r\n Yes, GATE consists of **29 papers**, each corresponding to a different discipline such as Civil Engineering, Computer Science, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, Biotechnology, Chemistry, Mathematics, and more. Candidates must choose one paper based on their qualifying degree or area of interest.\r\n\r\nIs there any age limit for appearing in GATE?\r\n No, there is **no upper age limit** for candidates appearing in GATE. Any graduate or final-year undergraduate student in the relevant disciplines is eligible to apply.\r\n', NULL, 1, 1, '2026-01-08 09:48:50', '2026-01-09 07:40:35'),
(60, 'PG', 1, 'All India Medical Process Neet PG (AIMP PG)', 'All India Medical Process Neet PG (AIMP PG)', './assets/images/AIMAP.jpeg', 'All India Medical Admission Process', 'Introduction\r\nThere will be four rounds of AIQ counseling i.e. Round 1, Round 2, AIQ third Round and AIQ Stray Vacancy RocfCF (Hon\'ble Supreme Court of India). All candidates who have qualified for All', 'Eligibility\r\nCandidate must have qualified NEET-PG.\r\n\r\nQuota Distribution\r\n•\r\n50% All India Quota seats of all states', 'Reservation Policy\r\nCategory	Reservation Percentage\r\nSchedule Caste and Schedule Caste converted to Buddhism (SC)	15%\r\nSchedule Tribe (ST)	7.5%\r\nOther Backward Category (OBC) Including SBC	27%\r\nEWS	10%\r\nPerson with Disability (PwD)	5%', 'Fee Structure\r\nCategory	NEET PG counselling fee	Security deposit\r\nCentral university General category candidates AIQ	Rs. 1000/-	Rs. 25,000/-\r\nSC/ ST/ OBC/ PwD category candidates	Rs. 500/-	Rs. 10,000/-\r\nDeemed University candidates	Rs. 5000/-	Rs. 2,00,000/-', 'Registration\r\n\r\nChoice Filling\r\n\r\nSeat Allotment\r\n\r\nSeat Acceptance\r\n\r\nReporting to the Designated College\r\n\r\nAdditional Rounds.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRequired Documents\r\n\r\nNEET PG admit card\r\n\r\nNEET PG result\r\n\r\nMark Sheets of MBBS/BDS professional examinations\r\n\r\nMBBS/BDS Degree Certificate\r\n\r\nInternship Completion Certificate\r\n\r\nRegistration certificate issued by MCI\r\n\r\nDate of birth proof\r\n\r\nValid ID proof\r\n\r\nCaste certificate\r\n\r\nDisability Certificate', 'FAQ\r\nHow many rounds of counseling are there in NEET PG?\r\nNEET PG 2024 Counselling is conducted in 4 rounds- round 1, round 2, mop up round, and stray vacancy round. NEET PG counselling process includes registration, choice filling & locking, seat allotment result, and reporting.\r\n\r\nWhat after NEET PG counselling round 1?\r\nAfter the release of the 2024 NEET PG allotment list for counselling round one, candidates will be required to follow the steps mentioned below based on their status.\r\n\r\n1\r\nFree exit:The seat allotted in the first round of MCC NEET PG counselling 2024 will be cancelled if a candidate does not report to the allotted institute within the stipulated time. Such an option is referred to as \'free exit\'.\r\n2\r\nAccepting the seat allotted in round one:If a candidate who has been allotted a seat in the first round of NEET PG 2024 counselling is satisfied with the allotted seat they can report to the allotted institute and secure their seat by paying tuition fee.\r\n3\r\nUpgradation in round 2: If a candidate is not satisfied with the seat allotted to them, they can opt for upgradation and participate in the second round of NEET PG counselling 2024. In case the seat is not upgraded during the second round, the seat allotted to the candidate in NEET PG counselling round one will be retained.\r\nWho are eligible for NEET PG 2024 counselling round two?\r\n•\r\nCandidates not allotted any seat in NEET PG counselling 2024 round one\r\n•\r\nCandidates whose seats allotted in NEET PG admission round one got cancelled in physical document verification\r\n•\r\nCandidates willing for up-gradation of the seat in the second round of NEET PG 2024 counselling\r\n•\r\nCandidates who opted for free exit or did not participate in the counselling of NEET PG round one.\r\nCandidates participating in round two of MCC NEET PG 2024 counselling must note that there is no option of \'free exit\' in the second round of counselling. If a candidate does not secure his/her NEET PG admission 2024 in the college/seat allotted during round two, his/her refundable security deposit will be forfeited.\r\n\r\nWhat is the Counseling Process of Neet Pg Mop-up Round ?\r\nThe NEET PG counselling mop-up round of MCC will be conducted only for admission to deemed and central universities and ESIC institutes.\r\n\r\n•\r\nFresh registration:Candidates who exited either round one or round two of NEET PG 2024 counselling by not reporting to the allotted college will be required to register again for the mop-up round.\r\n•\r\nNo new registration: Candidates who did not get any seat either in round one or in round two of NEET PG counselling will not be required to register again for the mop-up round.\r\n•\r\nChoice filling:All candidates will have to fill in fresh choices of courses and colleges.\r\n•\r\nSeat allotment:The NEET PG 2024 seat allotment of the mop-up round will be published on the official website', NULL, 1, 1, '2026-01-08 09:53:46', '2026-01-08 10:37:07');
